did.abstract: Documents the Supreme Court terms of William H. Rehnquist, associate justice from 1972 to 1986 and chief justice from 1986 to 2005. Materials include court case files, administrative files, conference files, correspondence, speeches and writings, book manuscripts, invitations, and other materials. Also includes Rehnquist's law school notebooks from his time at Stanford Law School in 1951 and 1952.

bioghist.head: Biographical Note
bioghist.p: Born on October 1, 1924 in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, William Hubbs Rehnquist served in the Army Air Corps in North Africa during World War II. Once the war ended he attended Stanford University, where he received a B.A. in political science. He then earned master's degrees from both Stanford and Harvard, before completing Stanford Law School in 1952. After completing law school, Rehnquist served as a clerk to Supreme Court Justice Robert H. Jackson.

Rehnquist married Natalie Cornell, whom he had met at Stanford during his law school years, on August 29, 1953. They had three children. Rehnquist practiced law in Phoenix, Arizona, from 1953 to 1969, becoming active in Republican politics during this time. Joining President Richard Nixon's administration in 1969 as head of the office of legal counsel in the Justice Department, in October 1971, President Nixon nominated Rehnquist to be an associate justice on the Supreme Court.

Rehnquist served as an associate justice until 1986, when President Ronald Reagan nominated him to replace retiring Chief Justice Warren Earl Burger. Rehnquist was the sixteenth Chief Justice, serving more than 30 years on the Supreme Court. He has the distinction of serving as the second Chief Justice in U.S. history to preside over an impeachment trial of a president, in 1999. A notable decision in Rehnquist's tenure as chief justice was Bush v. Gore (2000), which effectively decided the 2000 presidential election for George W. Bush by stopping the recount of contested ballots in Florida.

As Chief Justice, Rehnquist stated that his goal was to be remembered as a good administrator. Known for his strong leadership, conservative interpretation of the Constitution, and decisions enhancing the power of the states in the federal system, Rehnquist retained his conservative perspective throughout his tenure on the Court. Ill with thyroid cancer, Rehnquist served as Chief Justice as long as his health permitted. He died on September 3, 2005, in Arlington, Virginia, and is buried in Arlington National Cemetery.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content of Collection
scopecontent.p: The William H. Rehnquist papers mainly document Rehnquist's time as a justice of the United States Supreme Court, from 1972 to 1986, then as chief justice from 1986 to 2005. A small amount of material also documents Rehnquist's studies at Stanford Law School in 1951 and 1952.

The Stanford Law School Notebooks and Journal contain Rehnquist's class notes, with another volume documenting his accounts and personal journal entries with non-continuously dated portions from 1947 to 1965.

Documentation on the U.S. Supreme Court includes Administrative Files, which document the functional management of the court. Materials include stays, opinions, subject files, correspondence, conference and order lists, and vote sheets. Some administrative files contain collected information on subjects such as abortion cases or capital cases.

U.S. Supreme Court Case Files contain official printed drafts of each case opinion circulated among the justices. Some files also contain concise correspondence, memoranda, and other materials regarding the case. In many instances there are multiple cases within one file. Materials are organized by the court term, or October term, in which the case was heard.

The U.S. Supreme Court Administrative and Case Files from 1972 through 1974, and Rehnquist's Stanford Law School Notebooks and Journal were opened November 17, 2008. Printed Opinions and Syllabi, Correspondence, and materials on Rehnquist's books, as well as additional materials including speeches, writings, notebooks, and other documents, opened in August 2009.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Consists of both official and personal correspondence, dating from Justice Rehnquist's appointment to the Supreme Court until just before his death in 2005. The bulk of the correspondence concerns routine matters pertaining to Rehnquist's work schedule, his travel plans, and speaking engagements. The series also contains journal articles sent to Justice Rehnquist by legal scholars. The correspondence does not concern matters before the Supreme Court, nor does it contain substantive expositions of Justice Rehnquist's judicial philosophy. The finding aid indicates places (boxes 139, 144, and 171) where there is correspondence to and from other Supreme Court justices, again of a routine or personal nature.

At the beginning of the series there are a large number of letters of condolence sent to Justice Rehnquist on the occasion of his wife's death, as well as a separate grouping of letters of congratulation sent to him upon his appointment as Chief Justice. There is also a small amount of family correspondence at the end of the series.

The original order of the materials has been largely preserved: the correspondence is arranged chronologically as a succession of alphabetical files, with the time periods generally corresponding to the October to June terms.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: In addition to Rehnquist's many official remarks, largely pertaining to issues of constitutional law and the functioning of the American judicial system, this series includes a number of articles, as well as materials relating to his visiting lectureships at the University of Arizona and as part of summer programs run by American universities in the United Kingdom and Europe. There are also numerous speeches given on ceremonial occasions in which Rehnquist appeared in his capacity as Chief Justice of the United States.

The series contains a good deal of accompanying material, largely consisting of correspondence, and in some cases, printed matter used in the preparation of speeches. A number of folders contain neither speeches nor writings, but rather correspondence and other documents relating to various moot court panels that Rehnquist served on, meetings that he attended, and, in one case, his brief tenure, on special assignment, as a circuit justice. There are also a number of prints that depict Rehnquist at speaking engagements. It is noted in the register when only correspondence, and not the text itself, is available for a particular speech.
The original arrangement of the materials has been maintained.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Consists of invitations, correspondence, notes, event checklists, guest lists, menus, souvenirs, and photographs relating to events (both official Supreme Court functions and informal social occasions) to which Rehnquist was invited. Arranged in two subseries: Accepted, 1985-2003, and Declined, 1971-2005.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Consists of invitations, correspondence, notes, event checklists, guest lists, menus, souvenirs, and photographs relating to events attended by the Chief Justice. Documents official Supreme Court functions in addition to informal social occasions. Provides documentation of the Chief Justice's social circle, daily activities, hobbies, and the role of the Court among U.S. and international law community. Arranged in chronological order by the date the event was held. The months of July and August are absent for most years, since the court was not sitting during those months. Gaps in the collection exist for the months of September-December 1989, May-December 1991, June-October 1992, and June 1999

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Consists of invitations, correspondence and notes regarding events that Rehnquist declined to attend. From 1971-1979, the files reflect invitations to speak or judge moot court competitions. After 1980, the files also include social events. Arranged chronologically by date that the invitation was received. Beginning in October 1986 the invitations are separated by the October Term year (The Supreme Court term begins on the first Monday of October, so a letter dated in September 1987 would be filed with the 1986 October term), and are further subdivided alphabetically by the name of the person or institution extending the invitation. Significant gaps exist in October Terms 1989 and 1991. The entirety of Rehnquist's first year on the court, 1972, has been retained, along with the year he was nominated chief justice, 1986, and his last year on the court, 2004. For the years 1974-1985 and 1987-2003 a random representative sample of one fifth of the original materials are retained.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The notebooks contain a daily schedule including meetings, appointments, reminders, and notes from 1969-1980. Large monthly calendars include appointments and notes dating from 1973-2004, while smaller desk calendars contain daily notes from 1970-2005.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Consists of invitations, scripts, correspondence, oath cards, maps, and transcripts relating to official events in which the Chief Justice participated. Includes files documenting Rehnquist's own confirmation hearings, funerals and memorial services, presidential inaugurations, and Supreme Court investitures. Arranged by type of event, then chronologically.
